## 1. Map of Environmental Justice (EJ) Priority

```{r}
# Clean ID to match map
df2 <- df1_clean %>%
  select(Name, GEOID, CHAKNKC_2023) %>%
  mutate(GEOID = as.character(as.numeric(GEOID)))

# Downloaded the Chicago Neighborhood Boundaries
boundary_url <- "https://data.cityofchicago.org/resource/igwz-8jzy.geojson"
chicago_shapes <- st_read(boundary_url) %>% 
  st_transform(4326) %>%
  mutate(area_num = as.character(as.numeric(area_numbe))) # Changed ID to add

# Added the data to the map
map_data <- chicago_shapes %>%
  left_join(df2, by = c("area_num" = "GEOID"))

# Created Color Palette
pal <- colorNumeric(
  palette = "YlOrRd", 
  domain = map_data$CHAKNKC_2023[map_data$CHAKNKC_2023 > 0],
  na.color = "grey"
)

# Interactive Map
leaflet(map_data) %>%
  addTiles() %>%  # Background map
  addPolygons(# Colors for scores > 0, if not grey
    fillColor = ~ifelse(CHAKNKC_2023 == 0 | is.na(CHAKNKC_2023), "grey", pal(CHAKNKC_2023)),
    weight = 1.5,
    color = "white",      # Added boundaries for each neighborhood
    fillOpacity = 0.7,
    label = ~paste0(Name, ": ", CHAKNKC_2023), # Hover Label: Neighborhood Name
    popup = ~paste0("<strong>Neighborhood: </strong>", Name,  # Click: Shows Exact Number
                    "<br><strong>EJ Priority Score: </strong>", CHAKNKC_2023)
  ) %>%
  addLegend(
    pal = pal, 
    values = ~CHAKNKC_2023, 
    title = "EJ Priority Score"
  )
```

*The interactive map of Environmental Justice Priority Scores demonstrates a spatial disparity across Chicago. Areas with high priority scores are predominantly located in the west and south side neighborhoods, indicating that the higher cumulative burden of environmental and socioeconomic vulnerability are likely to be found in these areas. On the other hand, the North and downtown areas revealed lower scores. This visualization serves as a baseline for our project, highlighting the specific communities where the health outcomes are likely to be impacted by environmental factors.*



## 2. Green vs. Gray: Parks and Traffic Maps

```{r}
library(leafsync)

df_env <- df1_clean %>%
  mutate(GEOID = as.character(as.numeric(GEOID)))

map_env <- chicago_shapes %>%
  left_join(df_env, by = c("area_num" = "GEOID"))

pal_parks <- colorNumeric("Greens", domain = map_env$PMC_2020, na.color = "grey")
pal_traffic <- colorNumeric("OrRd", domain = map_env$TRF_2020, na.color = "grey")

# Park Coverage map
map_parks <- leaflet(map_env) %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addPolygons(
    fillColor = ~pal_parks(PMC_2020),
    weight = 1.5, color = "white", fillOpacity = 0.7,
    label = ~paste0(Name, ": ", round(PMC_2020, 1))
  ) %>%
  addLegend(pal = pal_parks, values = ~PMC_2020, title = "Park Coverage", position = "bottomright")

# Traffic risk map
map_traffic <- leaflet(map_env) %>%
  addTiles() %>%
  addPolygons(
    fillColor = ~pal_traffic(TRF_2020),
    weight = 1.5, color = "white", fillOpacity = 0.7,
    label = ~paste0(Name, ": ", round(TRF_2020, 1))
  ) %>%
  addLegend(pal = pal_traffic, values = ~TRF_2020, title = "Traffic Exposure", position = "bottomright")

# Side by side sync
sync(map_parks, map_traffic)
```

*Park coverage and traffic exposure are the two opposite environmental forces, where park access enhances health, while traffic exposure is a stressor. Mapping both factors together allowed us to visualize the distribution of the environmental benefits and the harms equally across the Chicago neighborhoods. The park access map shows a darker green on the western and southern side of Chicago community areas, while there is still a uniform score across Chicago. The traffic map demonstrated only one or two neighborhoods near the West side and Loop area with high exposures, indicated by dark red. This concentration suggests that the highway interchanges in these areas could be a possible driver. The finding is that the neighborhoods with the highest traffic burden are not the same areas with the highest park access. The mismatch, therefore, illustrates an environmental injustice. The communities that are absorbing the most harm are not compensated by green spaces. While the South and west sides have high park access, they still have a high environmental justice burden from the previous plot, meaning the parks are not protective enough against other stressors.*



