## 4. Population vs EJ Priority
For context, Environmental Justice (EJ) priority areas are communities that face a disproportionate burden of pollution, hazardous waste, and health disparities. They're typically low-income neighborhoods and communities of color that are specifically targeted for policy intervention and investment. This visualization plots each Chicago neighborhood's total population against the number of residents living within EJ priority areas. The goal is to identify which neighborhoods carry the heaviest EJ burden... not just in raw numbers, but relative to their size. A neighborhood with a small population but a high number of EJ residents tells a very different story than a large neighborhood with the same count, and this scatter plot makes those distinctions immediately visible through interactivity.

```{r}
# need to use Population (x axis) and CHAKNKC_2023, or the number of residents in environmental justice priority areas (y axis)
# made a specific df for this plot so that it doesn't overwrite and interfere with components on future/previous dataframes
df_popvsej <- df1_clean |> mutate(
  Population = as.numeric(Population)) |>
 mutate(text = paste( "<span style='font-size:16px;'><b>", Name, "</b></span><br>", # makes a title of sorts to highlight each neighborhood name
    "\nPopulation: ", Population,
    "\nResidents in Eviornmental Justice Areas: ", CHAKNKC_2023)
  )

# i made a new column containing text so that tooltip would be customized to the text that i wanted with proper labeling

popvsej <- ggplot(df_popvsej, aes(x = Population, y = CHAKNKC_2023, fill = Name, text=text)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6, size = 3) +
  labs( title = "Population vs EJ Priority",
    x = "Total Population",
    y = "Residents in Enviornmental Justice areas"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() + theme()

ggplotly(popvsej, tooltip= "text")


```

It is to note that all neighborhoods that fall along the x-axis directly are neighborhoods that DO NOT have any residents living in at risk.
The legend doesn't serve the purpose of a traditional legend; the interactivity that ggplotly provides helps to easily find a specific neighborhood, as they're listed in alphabetical order. Selecting any neighborhood on that list will allow you to help isolate and identify where it is on the plot. The scatter plot reveals a clear divide between neighborhoods that have essentially no EJ residents at all, being clustered flat along the x-axis, and those that carry an enormously disproportionate burden. The neighborhoods sitting along the x-axis are areas where zero or near-zero residents fall within EJ priority designations, suggesting relatively lower environmental and health stressors. On the other end, neighborhoods like West Garfield Park and Burnside stand out sharply. Burnside in particular is extremely interesting because with a population of only 2,514, it has 2,509 residents in EJ priority areas. This implies nearly the entire neighborhood lives under environmental justice burden conditions. 

To break this down even further, here is a look at the top 15 neighborhoods exeriencing the most EJ burden, according to the ratio between EJ-affected residents, and the total population in that neighborhood as a whole
```{r}
df_popvsej_ratio <- df_popvsej |>
  mutate(
    EJ_ratio = CHAKNKC_2023 / Population #dividing EJ by population to get percentages
  )

top15_popvsej <- df_popvsej_ratio |>
  arrange(desc(EJ_ratio)) |>
  slice(1:15)

top15_popvsej |>
  mutate(EJ_ratio = scales::percent(EJ_ratio, accuracy = 0.1)) |>
  select(Name, Population, CHAKNKC_2023, EJ_ratio)

```

The top 15 EJ ratio table reinforces what was assumed earlier; the neighborhoods with the highest burden are not necessarily the largest ones. South Lawndale, North Lawndale, and West Garfield Park all appear in the top 15 despite having moderate populations, suggesting that geography and disinvestment, not just population size, are the primary drivers of EJ designation. Austin, the most "popular" neighborhood in the dataset at 96,753 residents, also appears in the top 15 with a 74.3% EJ ratio, meaning that even at scale, nearly three quarters of its residents live under these conditions.


## 5. Air Quality Perception vs Asthma (The Gap)
 
# Goal: highlight neighborhoods where residents think air quality is good, however asthma rates are high. 

```{r}
p1 <- ggplot(df1_clean, aes(
  x = CHASBQJ_2023.2024, #x-axis: residents’ perception of air quality
  y = HCSATH_2023.2024, #y-axis: clinically measured asthma rates
  text = paste( #For interactivity 
    "Neighborhood:", Name,
    "<br>Perception:", CHASBQJ_2023.2024,
    "<br>Asthma:", HCSATH_2023.2024
  )
)) +

# To plot each neighborhood as a point:
  geom_point(aes(color = HCSATH_2023.2024), size = 3, alpha = 0.8) +
  scale_color_viridis_c() + #color represents asthma severity. Chose transparent to show overlap

# Adding labels and title
  labs(
    x = "Good/Excellent Air Quality % Reported",
    y = "Adults with Asthma %",
    title = "Residents Perception vs Asthma Rates"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

# Adding interactivity
ggplotly(p1, tooltip = "text")

```

*The purpose of this plot is to compare residents’ perception of air quality with actual clinical asthma rates across neighborhoods. Each point represents a neighborhood, and the color intensity reflects asthma severity. We can easily identify mismatches between perception and reality from this visualization. If residents’ perception would match asthma rates, we would see a pattern where better perceived air quality matches with lower asthma rates. Neighborhoods located in the bottom-right show high perceived air quality as well as high asthma rates. This suggests that residents might underestimate or overestimate environmental health risks in their area. This visualization was created to highlight gaps in awareness and identify which neighborhoods might underestimate environmental risks.* 


## 6. Neighborhood Environmental Profiles

*Goal: Compare four specific neighborhoods to show how their "environmental personalities" differ.*

```{r}
# Select four neighborhoods
selected_neighborhoods <- df1_clean %>%
  filter(Name %in% c("Austin", "Englewood", "Lincoln Park", "Hyde Park"))

# To keep only the relevant variables
radar_data <- selected_neighborhoods %>%
  select(Name, CHABXHK_2023.2024, CHASBQJ_2023.2024, TRF_2020)

# To normalize values (0–1 scale so variables are comparable)
radar_scaled <- radar_data %>%
  mutate(across(-Name, ~ (. - min(.)) / (max(.) - min(.))))

# Create radar chart
fig <- plot_ly(type = 'scatterpolar', fill = 'toself')

for(i in 1:nrow(radar_scaled)) {
  fig <- fig %>%
    add_trace(
      r = as.numeric(radar_scaled[i, -1]),  # Values for each variable
      theta = c("Trust", "Perception", "Traffic"), # Axis labels
      name = radar_scaled$Name[i]           # Neighborhood name
    )
}

# Layout
fig <- fig %>%
  plotly::layout(
    title = "Neighborhood Environmental Profiles",
    polar = list(radialaxis = list(visible = TRUE))
  )

fig
```

*The purpose of this plot is to compare four neighborhoods across three dimensions: trust in government decisions about pollution, perceived air quality, and traffic exposure. Each neighbor has its own range that allows to highlight relative differences between the neighborhoods to have direct comparison across different types of measures. This visualization is useful for identifying patterns in how neighborhoods perceive environmental conditions. A neighborhood with high exposure to traffic and high perceived air quality could indicate lack of awareness of pollution sources. Similarly, when trust levels deviate from each neighborhood we can highlight their confidence in government decisions.*


