## 11. Park Access vs. Obesity 

```{r}
# Create North, South, and Central separation of the Chicago Neighborhoods. 
quantile(df1_clean$Latitude, c(0.33, 0.67)) 
#The quantile function helps calculate the values that divide ranked data into specified equal-sized groups. Since we're trying to separate these into 3 equal sections (not considering east because that's mainly just the lake), we take 1/3 (0.33) and 2/3 (0.67). So this returns exact latitude points in which less than 0.33% implies the Southern area, between 0.33% - 0.67% implies the Central separation (middle section), and greater than 0.67% are the Northern Neighborhoods. This can be done in as many sections as we need (For example, I could have done 4, but out of not wanting to accidentally mix neighborhoods from the east side up, I kept it to 3)

#now we need to create basically multiple "if-else" statements (using case_when) to make the sections: 

df1_clean <- df1_clean %>%
  mutate(result = case_when(Latitude < 41.78060 ~ "South", 
  41.78060 < Latitude & Latitude < 41.89917 ~ "Central", 
  TRUE ~ "North"), #Everything else will fall under north basically. everything that hasn't been accounted for. 
  result = as.factor(result) #This changes the existing character of result into a vector for us to actually use in the graph as a color result. 
  )
# Make the Hover text : 
df1_clean <- df1_clean |>
  mutate(hover_label = paste0(
      "Name: ", Name,
      "<br>Population: ", Population,
