## 12. The Clinical Comorbidity Heatmap

```{r}
#First, we need to create clean and converted variables. 

#To find if there are any NA values in the 4 health condition variables, You can summarize the column values and see if there are any and if they're spread among different columns or just for one particular one. 

colSums(is.na(df1_clean[, c("HCSOB_2023.2024", "HCSHYT_2023.2024", "HCSDIA_2023.2024", "HCSATH_2023.2024")]))
#Asthma and Diabetes has some NA's but not many.. is it worth removing those and messing with the data? Can we work around it? This could have happened because they weren't tested in particular locations, could be due to having such small populations that it wouldn't build reliable values/estimates, and more. 

#use cor() with pairwise.complete.obs, which uses all available non missing pairs for each calculation. Since we're only missng 3 and 5 in the other two categories, we can test and see if it creates a big difference before we move into interactivity. 

ds <- df1_clean %>%  #Have to use select function here, otherwise it will read the data p
  select(
  "Obesity" = HCSOB_2023.2024, 
  "Hypertension" = HCSHYT_2023.2024, 
  "Diabetes" = HCSDIA_2023.2024,
  "Asthma" = HCSATH_2023.2024)

corr<- cor(ds, use = "pairwise.complete.obs") #gives the correlation matrix with parts excluding the NA values. 
#Obesity and hypertension has a correlation of 0.877, meaning there's a strong relationship between the two and if a person is obese they most likely also have hypertension. Same with diabetes, with a correlation of 0.879. An even stronger relationship. Obesity and Asthma have a smaller relationship (0.767) since asthma can be affected by environmental factors. BUT it's still strong enough to suggest there is some relationship. The weakest relationship here is between Diabetes and Asthma (0.685), which reinforces that asthma is backed up by some other factor compared to the other three. 

#Make the matrix into a data frame: 
corr_d <- as.data.frame(as.table(corr)) #right now, as.data.frame takes the matrix and turns it into a data set, as.table displays the data as variable 1 vs. Variable 2, and the correlation between those two values. Returning 16 data point. 
colnames(corr_d) <- c("Health_Condition1", "Health_Condition2", "Correlation")
corr_d$Health_Condition1 <- as.character(corr_d$Health_Condition1)
corr_d$Health_Condition2 <- as.character(corr_d$Health_Condition2)
corr_d <- corr_d %>%
  mutate(relationship = case_when(
    abs(Correlation) > 0.8 ~ "Very Strong",
    abs(Correlation) > 0.6 ~ "Strong",
    abs(Correlation) > 0.4 ~ "moderate",
    TRUE ~ "Weak"
  )) 
corr_d <- corr_d |>
  mutate(hover_text = paste0(
      "Comparision: ", Health_Condition1 , " vs " , Health_Condition2,
      "<br>Correlation: ", round(Correlation, 3),
      "<br>Relationship: ", relationship
    ))
  
   
#NOW Interactivity: 

# press <- ggplotly(heat, tooltip = "text") %>% 
#   style(text = corr_d$hover_text, 
#         traces = 1:length(corr))  #1:length(corr) makes sure thee text is applied to EACH square.. 

plot_ly(
  data = corr_d,
  x = ~Health_Condition1,
  y = ~Health_Condition2,
  z = ~Correlation,
  zmin = 0.5,
  zmax = 1,
  #colorscale = list(c(0, "white"), C(1,"red")),
  type = "heatmap",
  xgap = 2,
  ygap = 2, 
#   #mode = "markers",
    hovertext = ~hover_text,
    hoverinfo = "text") |>
  plotly::layout(
     title = list(text = "Correlation Heatmap: Health Conditions", x = 0))
```

## What Does This Plot Mean?: 
*This plot is intended to show the correlation between all 4 of the health conditions that the data set includes to see how the conditions may relate to themselves. Each Correlation made for the map is calculated using all the data excluding the NA values for that specific variable combination. The resulting correlation matrix contains 16 rows, one for every variable pair including a pair with itself (so 4x4). The tooltip here is constructed so it gives additional information about each individual cell. This contains the comparison, the exact value of the correlation coefficient, and an interpretation of what that relationship means (if it's strong vs. weak). 
This is an important correlation to make because in the actual data, you may be able to look up the individual health conditions rates for a specific neighborhood. But there isn't really a method that can be used to show how those conditions may relate to each other across the city. The heatmap reveals that obesity, hypertension, and diabetes move together with a correlation of 0.877 between obesity and hypertension and 0.879 for obesity and diabetes. So that indicates that neighborhoods with high obesity will most likely carry high hypertension and diabetes Asthma, on the other hand, has noticeably weaker correlations between the other three health conditions (0.685, 0.794, 0.767 - respective to the graph). This means that the Asthma condition may be driven by different factors like air quality, housing conditions, and other environmental conditions. 
One thing to note is that there were NA values in the diabetes and asthma data sets, which may be a reflection of the community and the area itself. It might be because the population sizes were too small for reliable data to be pulled from that area, for example. Another thing is that these correlations partly reflect the population since the health conditions had to be made into percentages. So they don't solely reflect the health conditions independently. Despite these limitations, the correlations across all the pairs demonstrate a compelling case that these conditions are geographically driven across communities in Chicago.*



