## 14. The North-South Health Divide
For context for these next 2 plots, it first needs to be described what a Cumulative Health Index is. A Cumulative Health Index is a comprehensive measure of a community's overall health status, calculated by summing multiple health outcomes, deficits, or environmental stressors over time. It signifies the total accumulated burden of diseases, risks, and stressors rather than a single illness, frequently used to assess aging (frailty) or community vulnerability to pollution. Obesity, Hypertension, Diabetes, and Asthma are all health factors we have been looking at throughout this document. This index allows for a fair, comparable measure of health across all 77 Chicago neighborhoods. The goal of this visualization is to examine whether health burden follows a geographic pattern. More specifically, whether neighborhoods in the South, Central, or North regions of Chicago carry systematically different levels of cumulative health burden.

```{r}
# building a health index (mix of scales, so normalize each one); all health outcomes will be summarized.
df1_clean <- df1_clean %>%
  mutate(
    OB_pct  = HCSOB_2023.2024,                          # already a percentage
    HYT_pct = HCSHYT_2023.2024,                         # already a percentage
    DIA_pct = (HCSDIA_2023.2024 / Population) * 100,    # count → percentage
    ATH_pct = (HCSATH_2023.2024 / Population) * 100,    # count → percentage
    Health_Index = rowMeans(cbind(OB_pct, HYT_pct, DIA_pct, ATH_pct), na.rm = TRUE)
  )


summary(df1_clean$Health_Index)
```


```{r}

df1_clean <- df1_clean %>%
  mutate(hover_box = paste0( # creating a column for the tooltip identifiers
    "<span style='font-size:16px;'><b>", Name, "</b></span><br>", # makes a title of sorts to highlight each neighborhood name
    "<br>Region: ", result,
    "<br>Health Index: ", round(Health_Index, 2), "%",
    "<br>Obesity Rate: ", round(OB_pct, 1), "%",
    "<br>Hypertension Rate: ", round(HYT_pct, 1), "%",
    "<br>Diabetes Rate: ", round(DIA_pct, 1), "%",
    "<br>Asthma Rate: ", round(ATH_pct, 1), "%"
  ))

# creating the visualization
plot_geo <- ggplot(df1_clean, aes(x = result, y = Health_Index, fill = result, text = hover_box)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.5, outlier.shape = NA) +
  geom_jitter(aes(text = hover_box), width = 0.15, alpha = 0.5, size = 2) +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = c("South", "Central", "North")) +
  labs(
    title = "North-South Health Divide",
    x = "Region (Binned Latitude)",
    y = "Cumulative Health Index (%)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

ggplotly(plot_geo, tooltip = "text")

```

The boxplot reveals a meaningful geographic pattern in health burden across Chicago's regions. The South region displays the widest spread of values, with several neighborhoods reaching Health Index scores above 8%, and its median sitting around 3.5%. The Central region shows the most compressed distribution, with most neighborhoods clustering between roughly 3-5%, though it contains a notable high outlier approaching 16%-- Austin. The North region, interestingly, shows a slightly higher median and tighter upper range compared to South, which may seem contradictory. However this likely reflects that the North region contains both very wealthy low-burden neighborhoods and some moderate-burden ones, pulling the box upward without extreme outliers. The individual jittered points are important here. They show that within each region there is substantial variation, meaning the regional label alone doesn't determine a neighborhood's fate. The interactive tooltip allows you to hover over any individual point to see the full breakdown of all four health conditions, which helps identify which specific condition is driving a neighborhood's index score up.



## 15. EJ Burden vs. Cumulative Health
For this final visualization, having established what EJ priority areas are, how they're distributed across Chicago's neighborhoods, and how health outcomes vary geographically, this plot tests the question does living in an environmentally burdened community predict worse clinical health outcomes? The x-axis represents the number of residents in EJ priority areas for each neighborhood, and the y-axis represents the Cumulative Health Index calculated from the four health conditions tracked throughout this document. A regression line is overlaid to show the overall directional trend. If the line slopes upward, it provides statistical evidence that higher EJ burden corresponds to higher cumulative health burden, connecting environmental conditions to clinical outcomes at the neighborhood level.

```{r}
df1_clean <- df1_clean %>%
  mutate(hover_final = paste0(
    "<span style='font-size:16px;'><b>", Name, "</b></span><br>", # makes a title of sorts to highlight each neighborhood name
    "<br>Region: ", result,
    "<br>EJ Residents: ", CHAKNKC_2023,
    "<br>Health Index: ", round(Health_Index, 2), "%",
    "<br>Obesity Rate: ", round(OB_pct, 1), "%",
    "<br>Hypertension Rate: ", round(HYT_pct, 1), "%",
    "<br>Diabetes Rate: ", round(DIA_pct, 1), "%",
    "<br>Asthma Rate: ", round(ATH_pct, 1), "%"
  ))
# creating the visualization
plot_final <- ggplot(df1_clean, aes(x = as.numeric(CHAKNKC_2023), y = Health_Index, color = result, text = hover_final)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6, size = 3) +
  
  geom_smooth(aes(group = 1), method = "lm", se = TRUE,
              color = "black", linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(
    title = "EJ Burden vs. Cumulative Health Index",
    x = "Residents in EJ Priority Areas",
    y = "Cumulative Health Index (%)",
    color = "Region"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

ggplotly(plot_final, tooltip = "text")
```
The scatter plot and its regression line together make a compelling case. The dashed regression line has a clear positive slope, meaning that as the number of EJ priority residents in a neighborhood increases, the Cumulative Health Index rises as well. The shaded confidence band around the line remains relatively narrow through the middle range of EJ values before widening at the upper end, which is expected given that fewer neighborhoods exist at extreme EJ burden levels. The color coding by region adds another layer. North neighborhoods (green) cluster heavily toward the left of the x-axis with low EJ resident counts, while Central (pink) and South (blue) neighborhoods are more spread across the x-axis, with several appearing at higher EJ values. The one point sitting at the far right of the plot at roughly 70,000 EJ residents and a Health Index near 16%, once again Austin, acts as a powerful anchor for the regression line and illustrates just how extreme the burden concentration can be. Taken together, this plot does not just describe health disparities in Chicago. It visually supports the argument that environmental burden and clinical health outcomes are linked, and that the neighborhoods carrying the most EJ weight are also the ones where residents are most likely to be living with obesity, hypertension, diabetes, and asthma simultaneously.

